Side Plank or vasisthasana variations

This pose is so beneficial in building both strength and balance in your body and in your practice. 

Did you know it can help with scoliosis?!
In a 2014 study Dr. Loren Fishman showed its potential benefits; the study found that after an average of 6.8 months, 19 of the 25 participants who practiced side plank on their weaker convex side (the side toward which the spine curved) for an average of 1.5 minutes a day, an average of 6.1 days a week, experienced marked improvement. Research like this is fascinating to me, because it proves the benefits of yoga in modern science rather than only the esoteric descriptions we learn.

Speaking of the esoteric, who is this pose named after?
Vasistha was the first of Brahma’s sons—one of the famous “seven sages” who form the constellation known in the West as the Pleiades. 
Vasistha was also the first teacher of jnana yoga, the path of self realization. One of his most well known students was Lord Rama.

How to do seated Compass Pose:

1. Inhale, and as you do, hold your left foot with your right hand. Your left hand should be placed on the floor, inside the left thigh (for support). When ready, lift the foot that you are holding, stretching out the leg. 
2. Exhale deeply and twist your hip slightly towards the right. Move your head so that it is positioned inside the right arm (the one stretched out and holding your left foot). 
3. Breathe and make sure you respect the boundaries of your physical ability, lean into the stretch as much as you can. 
4. Bend your knee as much as needed as you learn the posture. 
5. Hold the pose for around five breaths. (You can hold it for less or more depending on your own physical ability, and the intention of the pose). 
6. To increase the fun and excitement try it standing. 😉

Yoga Posture Transition Challenge Fun 🤩 

From Malasana/Garland Pose, take the bind around one shin and your low back.

As you lift your hips, bring your other foot towards the midline. Press down with the unbound leg as you stand up into a standing Marichyasana A or Flamingo 🦩 Pose.

Once you’re standing, release the bind (challenge!) don’t let the lifted foot touch the ground as you switch into the bind for Bird of Paradise posture.

From Bird of Paradise slowly lower your lifted foot to the floor into a standing twist/half standing tittibhasana.

Try it on both sides.

PRO TIP🔥if you pretend the floor is hot lava it’s way more fun 🤩 #yogaismyrecess

Arm Balance Playtime 🥳

If this entire sequence is too much for you just pick one tiny part of it to practice and master. One chunk of learning at a time goes a long way.

Grasshopper Pose is the place to start. With one hand on the ground you feel supported but there’s still enough of a Balance challenge that you must keep your Drishti aka gaze point strong and steady as well as keep your breath regulated.

Dragonfly Pose is where we take it into a full arm balance. If you struggle with your foot slipping off your arm, especially in hot yoga, try setting the opposite hip directly behind the foot to keep it in place even when you are sweaty 🥵. 

Side Staff Pose was the first really complex foot behind head pose i was ever able to do. Go slow and steady with this not rushing anything including the time it takes to learn the pose.

As a Vinyasa Yoga Teacher, I encourage creativity and following your own intuition. 

I encourage you to listen to your body and breath more intimately than you adhere to the sound of my voice. You are the authority governing you when you attend yoga class. 

So that means…
✨Make the yoga poses easier or more difficult for yourself by listening to the quality of your breath. 

✨Take an easier pose for your body’s unique tendencies and needs.

✨Choose to do a different physical shape else that serves you better in the present moment.

The point of meditation is not to stop thinking, which would be a near impossible task because your mind is meant to move. With practice over time you can learn to concentrate and in turn, meditate.

Just try for one minute to sit and focus on your breathing. 

Set a timer. 

Notice how many times your mind wanders away from noticing your breath in that minute. 

Try it again tomorrow.

And the next day. 

You’ll begin to realize that thoughts will always be passing like clouds in the sky. Your breath, your anchor, your object of focus, keeps you tethered to the present moment.

Ear Pressure Pose / Karnapidasana 
I really love the effect this pose has on my shoulders and spine. I feel the greatest release in my shoulders in this pose—if you lift weights or are a parent lifting children, try this pose for some relief.

This pose is best learned in person with a teacher and some teachers won’t teach it. If you have a neck injury you should not be attempting it at all. The physical and mental benefits outweigh the risk for me so I practice it mindfully. You can reach back for your heels if you are completely steady and balanced and press down on your heels to encourage your knees to the floor. You can have your palms to the floor behind your back if you do not need them for balance. This pose is a way to experience The concept of pratyahara, withdrawal of the senses, physically, which is extra calming to me.

I see this alignment mistake quite often in yoga, and it makes sense because often our outer hips are weak so we compensate by lessening the weight on our pinky toe and allowing the load bearing knee to drop in towards the midline. You can counteract this by 1) becoming aware that it’s happening 2) deliberately put the weight into your pinky toe and track your knee over your ankle 3) it can help to not sit as low in the pose as you build that outer hip strength, and then in time as you’re ready reattempt the full version of Warrior 2.

EYE YOGA EXERCISES 
Open your eyes, then check on your posture. Is your spine straight? Hands on the knees? Body relaxed? Head straight? That is how you should always remain while doing eye exercises. The whole body must be motionless; nothing must move except the eyes.
Now raise your eyes and find a small point that you can see clearly without straining, without frowning, without becom ing tense and, of course, without moving your head. Breathing should be normal.
TECHNIQUE:
1. (a) Raise the eyes to look at your chosen high point.
(b) Lower the eyes to look at your chosen low point.
Repeat four times. Close the eyes and rest a moment. (I skipped this because I only have 90 seconds to film a reel.)
2. Now do the same using points to your right and to your left, at eye level. Moving only the eyes, look to the right at your chosen point, then to the left. Repeat four times. Blink several times, then close your eyes and rest. (I skipped this because I only have 90 seconds to film a reel.)
3. Next choose a point you can see from the right corner of your eyes when you raise them, and another that you can see from the left corner of your eyes when you lower them, half closing the lids. Remember to retain your original posture-spine erect, hands on knees, head straight and motionless.
Look at your chosen point in right corner up, then to the one in left corner down. Repeat four times. Blink several times.
Close the eyes and rest. (I skipped this because I only have 90 seconds to film a reel.)
Do the same exercise in reverse. That is, first look to the left corner up, then to the right corner down. Repeat four times.

Third Eye Chakra / ajna 

The third eye chakra, also known as the Ajna chakra, is the center of intuition, perception, and spiritual insight. Here are four yoga poses that can help balance and activate this chakra:

1. Downward-Facing Dog (Adho Mukha Svanasana): Begin on your hands and knees, then lift your hips up and back while straightening your arms and legs. Spread your fingers and press your hands into the ground, while lengthening your spine and keeping your head between your arms.
2. Shoulder Stand (Sarvangasana): Lie on your back and lift your legs up toward the ceiling, then use your hands to support your hips as you raise your legs over your head. Keep your arms and hands on the ground and hold the pose for several breaths. Shoulder stand is a powerful pose that helps to activate the third eye and stimulate the thyroid gland.
3. Child's Pose (Balasana): Begin on your hands and knees, then sit back on your heels while stretching your arms forward. Rest your forehead on the ground and breathe deeply. This pose stimulates the third eye and calms the mind.
4. Eagle Pose (Garudasana): Start by standing with your feet hip-width apart. Cross your right arm over your left arm and bend both elbows, wrapping your forearms around each other. Then cross your right leg over your left leg and hook your right foot behind your left calf. Hold the pose for several breaths and then repeat on the other side. Eagle pose helps to improve focus and concentration.

Welcome to Day 7 of the Chakra Cruise 🚢💜
Crown Chakra / sahasrara

I know I’m technically home in Utah now 😉and the cruise is over, but I’ve got to share some yoga poses for the crown chakra 💜💜💜✨✨✨

The Crown Chakra, or Sahasrara, is the seventh primary chakra located at the top of the head. It is associated with spiritual connection, consciousness, and enlightenment. 

Here are four yoga poses that can help activate and balance the Crown Chakra:
1. Headstand (Sirsasana): Thanks to @kels.yoga for demoing headstand with me in a few of these videos 💜 🙏🏼✨ This inversion pose stimulates the crown chakra and promotes clarity and mental focus. To perform headstand, come onto your hands and knees, interlace your fingers, and place your forearms on the ground. Place the top of your head on the ground and straighten your legs. Slowly lift your legs off the ground and come into a full headstand.
2. Half Lotus Pose (Ardha Padmasana): This seated pose stretches the hips and lower back while stimulating the crown chakra. Sit on the floor with your legs straight out in front of you. Bend your right knee and place your right foot on top of your left thigh. Place your left hand on your left knee and your right hand on your right foot. Close your eyes and breathe deeply.
3. Corpse Pose (Savasana): This relaxation pose helps to calm the mind and promote mental clarity. Lie down on your back with your arms at your sides and your palms facing up. Close your eyes and take slow, deep breaths. Imagine a white light surrounding your body and filling your mind with peace and tranquility.
4. Lotus Pose (Padmasana): This seated pose helps to open the Crown Chakra and promote spiritual connection. Sit on the floor with your legs crossed and your feet on top of your opposite thighs. Place your hands on your knees, close your eyes, and breathe deeply. Imagine a violet light filling your Crown Chakra and connecting you to the universe.

The Dos and Don’ts of Headstand

First of all standing on your head doesn’t make you more of or less of a yogi. It’s simply another shape to move your body into mindfully while consciously breathing. 

DO🚦make sure the top of your head is on the ground—NOT 🚫 on your forehead

DO 🚦utilize your abdominal and pelvic floor muscles to lift your legs off the floor

DO 🚦support your neck in headstand

DO 🚦create a triangle base for tripod headstand 

Most importantly go SLOW. It took me 5 years of yoga practice plus a year dedicated just to mastering this skill. I’m a slow learner, but once I learn, I remember especially all the missteps because I’ve made them too. 🙈🤣

Things Studio Yoga Teachers Do Beyond Teaching Class🤓

I feel like a lot of new yoga teachers have romantic ideas about what it’s like to share your love of yoga with others, and I want to keep it real so you know what you’re signing up for. I have always taught in studios (and beyond), in 2020 I had a one month teaching break before studios began reopening in Utah. I feel very blessed that way, because I feel like there’s an energy exchange in in-person classes that simply cannot be transferred via zoom, you know? I’ve taken and taught classes and trainings both ways, and I definitely prefer being with you in person. 

There’s a lot of work and effort behind the scenes that makes a great yoga class experience. And I want to be honest here so new teachers know what studios are like and if they would enjoy teaching in that type of work environment. 

-setup/cleanup the yoga room: depending on the studio this could include any task from doing laundry, mopping floors, setting up props or candles like I’m doing in this video @purifywellnesscenter 💖😌

-pays for yoga teaching insurance: this can vary studio by studio. I have taught places that cover their instructors under their insurance policy and places where teachers are required to pay for their own. I currently pay for my own. If you teach at multiple studios or outside of studios I highly recommend carrying your own yoga insurance.

-takes Continuing Education courses. Growth is the wave of the future ~ you in? I have personally taken over a dozen (maybe more) Yoga Teacher Trainings.

-plans class before arriving to teach: not every style of yoga requires this, ie. if it is a set sequence, yet excellent teachers still put some intention behind even a set sequence. There are times I have planned an entire class and based on who shows up for class, I’ve had to forget the plan and adjust. This flexibility of mind allows you to teach the best class to the people with you in that moment. 

-creates a playlist for class, again some lineages offer no music. I understand the reasoning and realize music is a distraction from the one pointed focus we are cultivating in our yoga practice….but I love a good playlist

The breath through the asana hold as well as coming in and out of postures, is everything.

The breath is your direct link / access point to regulating your nervous system and managing your stress levels. That is why in yoga we place the body into specific geometric shapes while engaging certain muscles, maintaining specific points of eye gaze focus, lifting certain internal mechanisms—bandhas, and then you breathe intentionally and many times in specific ways or patterns to tone & strengthen your nervous system aka your relationship to stress.

And that is flipping awesome to me because I have stress in my life. 🤣🤪 Do you? Try yoga if you want. Any skill level can begin a beneficial yoga practice.

There is the gross, macro level of the physical body we work directly with in yoga postures. When you are able to get past the macro and aware of the micro, the subtle, you will see it reverberating in other ways too.

Breath, Bandhas, Drishti are the easiest access points to begin the harmonizing process.

avidyā-asmitā-rāga-dveṣa-abhiniveśaḥ kleśāḥ
Yoga Sutras 2.3 

Translation:
The five afflictions which disturb the equilibrium of consciousness are: ignorance or lack of wisdom, ego, pride of the ego or the sense of 'I’, attachment to pleasure, aversion to pain, fear of death and clinging to life.

B.K.S. Iyengar’s Commentary on this Sutra:
Afflictions are of three levels, intellectual, emotional and instinctive. Avidya and Asmita belong to the field of intelligence; here lack of spiritual know combined with pride or arrogance inflates the ego, causing conceit a loss of one's sense of balance. Raga and Dvesa belong to emotions and feelings. Raga is desire and attachment, dvesa is hatred and aversion. Succumbing to excessive desires and attachments or allowing oneself carried away by expressions of hatred, creates disharmony between and mind, which may lead to psychosomatic disorders. Abbinivesa is instinctive: the desire to prolong one's life, and concern for one's own survival. Clinging to life makes one suspicious in dealings with others, and one to become selfish and self-centred.

I found while teaching skills that were difficult if I could first teach them about their own thinking 💭 and mindset it helped both the learners and myself as the person helping them immensely.

From fixed mindset: I CAN’T ✋🏽

This little three-letter word YET gave them a chance. A chance to struggle with what didn’t come easy for them. A chance to embrace the confusion & overwhelm that is an innate part of the learning process and to keep going.

Improve your Spine Health
1) Properly Hydrate ~ the spinal discs are the sac of fluid between each vertebrae and are mostly composed of water. If we are not hydrated enough these discs shrink in size. Much of our spinal health and overall health for that matter is connected to these discs.

2) Strong Core & Pelvic Floor Muscles ~ I like to always consider the front and back side of the body as having a symbiotic relationship. To stabilize and support the spine and it’s movements, the core must be strong.

3) Yoga ~ Yoga postures like wheel, floor bow, low & high lunge are excellent for lengthening the spine, associated muscles and feeling better overall. These postures build better overall posture, and good posture is very important if you sit for long periods everyday. Notice if you hunch your shoulders or have forward head posture from looking at screens and devices, start to incorporate stretch’s and backbends in the opposite direction to balance yourself out.

Ishvara Pranidana is the last of the Niyamas, internal practices or observances to make progress on the yogic path. Swami Satchidananda in his translation of the Yoga Sutras makes it clear that if the practitioner of yoga can humble themselves enough to master this niyama then the rest are taken care of. 

What is Ishvara Pranidana?
It is the act of surrendering to a higher power, to God. This is the God of your own unique and personal understanding.

To be true with you this is the niyama that had me quite stalled in my yoga journey for quite some time.

Without getting too much into old stories, I was raised very strictly religious and by the time I was a young adult I was  quite turned off by the entire concept of a higher power or people receiving revelations on my behalf since from a young age I have always been intuitive. Yet at times in my young adulthood I labeled myself atheist or agnostic, but for me personally these were labels that simply expressed the internal wrestling I was experiencing in my own heart. 

The last few years especially the last several months, have humbled me to the point of knowing I know nothing.

My ego is a nice thing, it tells me which mouth to feed when I’m at the dinner table, but this dance of life cannot be controlled or manipulated by my own egoic sensibilities and inclinations.

I have been humbled time and time again to tears and being receptive to God’s hand in my life. I have given up old ways and habits thwarting my own growth and trajectory, and have chosen to be patient and have faith. To let go, and let God. It’s about time. 

End note:
Organized religion and a surrender to God are two very separate concepts. It is possible to be spiritual and not religious. It is possible to read spiritual texts and be holy yet not attend church. Yet, organized religion works for many people, it provides community and hope in a chaotic world. Find your own balance and truth this lifetime. This is one written expression of truth for me in this moment.

Here is the best daily habit to help: Daily Meditation

Meditation here and there is beneficial, but i personally didn’t see the benefits of this habit until I became consistent with it. It was the most difficult habit for me to want to do consistently, but once I experienced the benefits of it, I couldn’t go back.

Kundalini Frog Exercise 🐸
Why is this exercise one of my favorites?

I’ll share this first, I’ve had a baby without practicing these and after practicing them daily, I’d rather experience childbirth with the frog 🐸 exercise in my daily routine!

Also, when I experienced neuropathy in my legs after so childbirth nerve damage, frogs are what I did along with cycling & weightlifting to begin to feel my feet and legs again—it took time—and since I was doing so much to try to heal, I can’t exactly pinpoint the magic 🪄 bullet so I attribute all of those to feeling my legs 🦵 again.

YOU DON’T HAVE TO HAVE A CHILD TO EXPERIENCE BENEFITS FROM THIS EXERCISE 😊💪🏼 (okay I’ll stop yelling via capital letters😆)

Benefits from Kundalini Frogs 🐸:
If you sit at a desk for the majority of your day, take a break and do some of these to give your back and legs some relief and a true recharge.🖥️

If you feel stuck in life or blocked creatively, practice these!💫

If you want the energy of your sacral chakra/sexual energy to be unblocked and flowing, try frogs!❤️‍🔥

Start with 8.
From there, try 26.
Build your strength to do 54.
Work your way up to 108.

Your quadriceps may burn 🔥 the trick is to not stop the momentum and keep up. That will physically teach you to keep going when things are difficult. If you sit and wallow in the misery of your efforts I promise it will be twice as difficult. Get the rhythm of your breath going and simply GO!

I’ve timed these. It takes me 5 minutes to do 108. Maybe we could see how fast we can do these, kind of like a 100-meter dash, a 108 frog 🐸 dash 🏃🏻‍♀️😆.

As humans we are made to be resilient to survive, adapt, shift, and heal. Positive stress is essential for our brains to thrive and maintain plasticity.

I learned this first hand from my grandma 👵🏼 who is very sharp even though she’s got some years under her belt. 😉 She was explaining to me how frustrating some transitions in getting older were because people wanted to do everything for her. She was shared, “I can make my bed everyday. I can cook my food. I participate in different activities to keep my mind sharp.” And honestly she is not wrong and an inspiration to me that it’s never too late to keep learning and living, because acute positive stress propels us towards THRIVING through life not only surviving.

It’s only when stress is too overwhelming or extreme or prolonged or if we get too stuck in the gear ⚙️ of fear that we become overburdened by stress.

There’s so much we can do in this life, yet we have a finite supply of energy in our bodies our cellular apparatus. If you’re under too much stress read the following 👇🏽

Ask yourself: 
What is worth my expenditure of energy? 
Do I have to do everything? 
Can I delegate? 
Can I let a few things go to increase my quality of life? 
Or is this stress just for a season that I can endure because it will pass by soon?

We only level up by meeting challenges, rising to the occasion, but we must cultivate enough self awareness to know when too much is too much.

I thought, “This will be easy. I was a cheerleader 📣 in high school. I have had to smile longer.”

During this process as my mind 🧠 went on the journeys a mind will go on when sitting and smiling for an hour, I thought:
🧠How many times do I force a smile?
🧠How is smiling a cultural thing?
🧠How many times do I mask pain with a smile? 
🧠How does a smile change how I feel?
And on and on and on..

I realized through this process that I have made the ridiculous association that smiles are equated 🟰 with public performance and assessment. 

💝A lot of my life I have preformed, presented, and taught in front of groups of people and been expected to smile. I have decided that doesn’t make the smile and good intentions behind it less genuine. 😊

I am a naturally smiley person by nature. I love smiling almost as much as I love laughing. 😊🤣

The first time I went to NYC 🗽my friend said, “Alissa, you have got to stop smiling so much while walking through this city. That’s why all the crazy people are coming up to you.” It did happen enough times to notice. But being from a small place in Utah I didn’t know how else to show up in a big city. 

Right now I know someone who is going through a personally difficult time. This person shared with me the other day how they are purposely smiling throughout the day because it keeps them hopeful and they feel better when they smile.😊

My conclusion to this meditation experience is that whether I feel like I’m performing, my cheek muscles are numb, or I am attracting “crazy’s”, I am going to keep smiling.😊

I am going to keep smiling to share light in dark times. 😊🕯️♥️🤟🏽

Don’t dim your light because the mind has perceived darkness in the world, shine ✨ brighter to be a lighthouse for others. 🌟💫💫💫

Balance in this yoga posture, funky forearmstand / funky pincha, can be discovered in the alignment of your base. When you bring the planted hand in line with the elbow that is on the ground you can feel the alignment even in an asymmetrical shape. 

 

Where are you looking?

Where you are looking determines the outcome. If your eyes are darting around, so is your mind, and the body follows. Where you are looking is where your body will move. Steady your gaze and in turn so will your breath, your mind, and your body. 

Where are your roots?

In this shape the roots of your posture are flipped and then made uneven. Your roots are not your feet or legs in this pose. One hand and the opposite forearm and hand are your steady base in this position. Getting the alignment of your roots stable is essential here—hand and elbow alignment will do this for you.

Have a level of competency and control be fore just haphazardly attempting this position. The shoulders must be stable and strong enough to support you in this pose.

The Family of Warrior Poses in yoga consists of three main poses, although there are other postures considered warrior as well: 
Warrior 1 (Virabhadrasana I), Warrior 2 (Virabhadrasana II), and Warrior 3 (Virabhadrasana III) are the main 3 Warrior positions.
Reverse Warrior (Viparita Virabhadrasana) and Humble Warrior (Baddha Virabhadrasana) are other Warrior posture variations. 

These poses are named after a fierce warrior, Virabhadra, from Hindu mythology. Each Warrior pose has its unique alignment and benefits, contributing to strength, balance, and flexibility in different ways.

Which is your favorite Warrior pose?
I love Warrior II for both the stretch I get when I practice it. I also really appreciate the stability required in my feet and legs in the posture.

As a practitioner of yoga do you explore the practice beyond asana / yoga postures?

You can begin by applying aspects of the 8 limbs of yoga to your asana practice.

A very simple way to do this with #pratyahara or withdrawal of the senses is to close your eyes while in a steady position in your asana. Bring your attention inward so you’re gathering your energy towards your inner self and inner landscape instead of surveying the external environment.

With this being said, there are of course specific #drishti or gaze points for each asana. For this exercise you let go of those traditional gaze points and gather towards the inner vision instead.

Do you enjoy your yoga posture practice?

I do.

It’s what initially drew me to yoga.

After lifting weights the last 2 years, I realize now that I had put a mental limit on certain areas of my body being able to stretch in certain yoga poses.

The truth is I really I just don’t know how to operate a stronger body in certain poses yet. 🙃 

Every time I would go to Mysore class, I’d get asked if I caught my heels in #kapotasana and the answer was, “No to my toes,” or “halfway up my foot, my shoulders are tight.” I really didn’t feel like my shoulders could move like they used to. 

With the help of a teacher on New Year’s Day I was assisted into grabbing my heels again. My mind was blown, but the posture felt good. 

I didn’t think I could get into it again on my own, but I really tried to today and boom 💥 “hi heels.” Now it’s just getting my nervous system used to the pose again. 🪩

Celebrating these little wins helps me stay motivated to practice especially on the days where it just feels like work.

“Practice and all is coming.” K. Pattabhi Jois
